05568nam a22006735i 9780822395973DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223959737 a10.1515/97808223959732doi  a(DE-B1597)552247  a(OCoLC)1125507436  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a19422102aA Deleuzian Century? /cIan Buchanan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b5 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tMarxism and Dualism in Deleuze -- tThe Memory of Resistance -- tDeleuze and Materialism: One or Several Matters? -- tArt and Territory -- tDeleuze and Cultural Studies -- tImmanence and Transcendence in the Genesis of Form -- tComment peut-on etre deleuzien? Pursuing a Two-Fold Thought -- tMarx and Poststructuralist Philosophies of Difference -- tStraining to Hear (Deleuze) -- tDeleuze and the Body: Eluding Kafka's "Little Death Sentence" -- tDeleuze and the Three Powers of Literature and Philosophy: To Demystify, to Experiment, to Create -- tOverdetermined Oedipus: Mommy, Daddy, and Me as Desiring-Machine -- tDeleuze's Philosophy of the Concrete -- tFrom Multiplicities to Folds: On Style and Form in Deleuze -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMichel Foucault's suggestion that this century would become known as "Deleuzian" was considered by Gilles Deleuze himself to be a joke "meant to make people who like us laugh, and make everyone else livid." Whether serious or not, Foucault's prediction has had enough of an impact to raise concern about the potential "deification" of this enormously influential French philosopher. Seeking to counter such tendencies toward hagiography-not unknown, particularly since Deleuze's death-Ian Buchanan has assembled a collection of essays that constitute a critical and focused engagement with Deleuze and his work.Originally published as a special issue of South Atlantic Quarterly (Summer 1997), this volume includes essays from some of the most prominent American, Australian, British, and French scholars and translators of Deleuze's writing. These essays, ranging from film, television, art, and literature to philosophy, psychoanalysis, geology, and cultural studies, reflect the broad interests of Deleuze himself. Providing both an introduction and critique of Deleuze, this volume will engage those readers interested in literary and cultural theory, philosophy, and the future of those areas of study in which Deleuze worked.Contributors. Ronald Bogue, Ian Buchanan, André Pierre Colombat, Tom Conley, Manuel DeLanda, Tessa Dwyer, Jerry Aline Flieger, Eugene Holland, Fredric Jameson, Jean-Clet Martin, John Mullarkey, D. N. Rodowick, Horst Ruthrof, Charles J. Stivale  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh1 aColombat, Andre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchanan, Ian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStivale, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodowick, D, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Eugene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJameson, Fredric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuthrof, Horst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchanan, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlieger, Jerry, econtributor.